[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is Shadow Broker, a self-hosted open-source intelligence aggregation platform. One dashboard, one world map, and 60 plus live public data feeds streaming into it in real time. Aircraft positions via ADSB, maritime vessels via AIS, satellite orbits via published TLE'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data, seismic events, fires, weather, public CCTV streams from 13 sources across six countries, radio receiver networks, KiwiSDR, APRS, mesh task internet device search through Shodan,'

[00:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'conflict event mapping through GDELT, 6,300 GitHub stars, AGPL3 licensed. The code base is Python plus TypeScript plus Rust with a Docker Compose deployment'

[00:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and an optional model context protocol integration that lets an AI agent query the live feeds directly. The pitch is unusual but legitimate. This is the dashboard that civilian journalists, conflict researchers,'

[00:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disaster response teams, and aviation hobbyists already build manually from a dozen separate websites, except packaged into one self-hosted instance you actually own. Shadow Broker is an aggregator, not a collector. It does not'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gather any data itself. It connects to 60 plus existing public data sources, most of which have their own web dashboards already I covered, and pulls the real-time feeds into a single unified map interface. The aircraft'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tracking comes from the same ADSB receivers that power Flightradar24 and ADSB Exchange. The vessel tracking comes from public AIS data that the same way MarineTraffic and VesselFinder use. The'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'satellite orbits come from the published two-line element set data that NORAD publishes openly. The conflict event mapping comes from GDELT, an academic project that catalogs news'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reports of conflict events globally. None of this is classified. None of it is non-public. The readme is explicit about that. You know, the project\'s stated policy is that no restricted or'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'non-public data sources are used or accessible. The value is consolidation, not collection. The single map interface saves operators from juggling 15 browser tabs. The metrics here are unusual for an OSINT project. 6,300 GitHub stars and'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '989 forks, which puts Shadow Broker in the upper tier of self-hosted OSINT tools. Python at 61% of the code base, TypeScript at 35% for the map front end,'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Rust at 2 and 1/2% for the performance-critical streaming layer. The latest tagged release is version 0.9.79, which dropped on May 12th, 3 days before this video. The release cadence has been'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weekly or every other week for over a year. AGPL3 licensed, the strong copyleft license that prevents commercial wrappers from forking Shadow Broker and running it as a closed service without publishing changes.'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '60-plus integrated feeds, 35-plus toggleable map layers, 13 public CCTV sources across six countries, and an experimental decentralized mesh network for sharing aggregated views across peer'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shadow Broker instances. For a single maintainer project, the scope is genuinely impressive. The feature set covers what an actual OSINT operator would build by hand. Real-time aircraft tracking with commercial,'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'military tagged, and private jet filters. Useful for journalists tracking the movements of corporate or political figures who publish their tail numbers. Maritime vessel positions with AIS class filters. Satellite orbital tracking with'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pass prediction. Seismic event mapping. Active fire detection from satellite thermal imagery. Weather overlays. Public CCTV stream embeds from sources that already publish their cameras openly.'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Radio receiver networks. KiwiSDR for shortwave. APRS for amateur radio packet. Meshtastic for low-power mesh networks. Shodan integration for searching internet exposed devices by region.'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GDELT conflict event overlay. Synthetic aperture radar ground change detection if you bring your own NASA Earth data account. Time machine snapshot playback for replaying historical states. Right-click region dossiers that pull'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'satellite imagery, news, weather, and conflict data for an arbitrary location. And optionally, an agentic AI integration through model context protocol, so a chat assistant can query'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the feeds and produce briefings. Here\'s the dashboard actually running. What you are looking at is the unified map interface with multiple data layers enabled simultaneously. Aircraft, vessels, fires, conflict markers, and'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'satellite passes all overlaid on the same world map. The togglable layers are visible in the side panel. Right-click on any region and you get the dossier view. Current weather,'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recent seismic activity, active fires, news headlines, vessel and aircraft movements in the area. The whole interface is keyboard-driven for operators who use it daily. Getting Shadow Broker running on your own server'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is straightforward enough that any home lab operator can manage it. Clone the repository, copy the example environment file, drop in your Shodan API key if you want device search, your NASA Earth data'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'credentials if you want SAR ground change detection, your TLS certificate paths if you want HTTPS. Bring up the stack with one Docker compose command. The default deployment runs the aggregator service, the map'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'front end, the streaming layer, and a database for caching. The first start pulls the public feed data into the local cache, which can take a few minutes depending on which layers you have enabled. After that, point a browser at the local'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'URL and the map renders with live data within seconds. For larger deployments, the project ships Kubernetes helm charts. For the simplest case, a single Docker run with a few environment variables is enough. It\'s worth being'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clear about what Shadow Broker is and is not because the visual aesthetic is dramatic enough to raise reasonable questions. Shadowbroker aggregates public data sources only. ADS-B, AIS, satellite TLE, GDELT,'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'public webcams. These are the same feeds that journalists at Bellingcat, Reuters, and the Wall Street Journal use for open-source investigations. The same feeds that disaster response'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'teams use during wildfires and earthquakes. The same feeds that hobbyist aviation and maritime enthusiasts have used for years. None of them are classified. None of them require unauthorized access. The readme is explicit about that policy'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the code base reflects it. There are no exploit modules, no scraping of restricted endpoints, no authentication bypasses. The dark ops aesthetic is stylistic, not technical. That said,'

[06:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'OSINT tooling is a category where local laws vary. Some jurisdictions place restrictions on aggregating certain categories of public data, particularly camera feeds or radio reception. The'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standard advice applies. Know the rules where you live, configure the layers you actually have a legitimate reason to enable, and don\'t use the dossier feature to harass individuals. If you want to try'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shadowbroker, the fastest path is a Docker Compose stack from the repository. Clone, configure the environment file with whichever API keys you need for the layers you want, bring it up. The default deployment uses only the free, no key feeds: aircraft,'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vessels, satellites, fires, weather, GDELT, so you can evaluate the map interface without signing up for any third-party accounts. If you want Shodan or SAR detection, the'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'documentation walks through the credential setup. If you want the MCP integration with an AI agent, the project ships an open-claw compatible skill that exposes the feed queries as tools.'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The repository is linked in the description. If you actually run this software, run it for the use cases the open source OSINT community has been doing for years. Journalism, disaster response, research, education, and the'

[07:48] [scene:talk]
